    "synopsis": "In this chapter, Enoch receives revelations concerning the mechanics of lightning, thunder, and the celestial luminaries. [C] According to 1 Enoch, the angel reveals the hidden chambers from which lightning emerges and the laws governing the sun, moon, and stars. This passage reflects Second Temple fascination with <em>maaseh bereshit</em> (the work of creation) and <em>maaseh merkavah</em> (the divine chariot) — the two great domains of mystical speculation. The chapter bridges cosmology and theology: understanding creation's order is not merely scientific curiosity but recognition of divine sovereignty. [B] The underlying assumption is that the cosmos operates by divine decree, with angelic intermediaries managing its functions (cf. Job 38:22-35, where God questions Job about the 'storehouses of snow' and 'treasuries of hail'). The luminaries follow appointed paths, never deviating — a contrast to the rebellious Watchers who abandoned their assigned stations.",
    
